{"id":"1708.04205","submitter":"Richard Schwarz","authors":"Barbara Funk, Rudolf Dvorak and Richard Schwarz","title":"Exchange orbits - an interesting case of co-orbital motion","comments":"20 pages, 18 figures","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"astro-ph.EP","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  In this investigation we treat a special configuration of two celestial\nbodies in 1:1 mean motion resonance namely the so-called exchange orbits. There\nexist -- at least -- theoretically -- two different types: the exchange-a\norbits and the exchange-e orbits. The first one is the following: two celestial\nbodies are in orbit around a central body with almost the same semi-major axes\non circular orbits. Because of the relatively small differences in semi-major\naxes they meet from time to time and exchange their semi-major axes. The inner\none then moves outside the other planet and vice versa. The second\nconfiguration one is the following: two planets are moving on nearly the same\norbit with respect to the semi-major axes, one on a circular orbit and the\nother one on an eccentric one. During their dynamical evolution they change the\ncharacteristics of the orbit, the circular one becomes an elliptic one whereas\nthe elliptic one changes its shape to a circle. This 'game' repeats\nperiodically. In this new study we extend the numerical computations for both\nof these exchange orbits to the three dimensional case and in another extension\ntreat also the problem when these orbits are perturbed from a fourth body. Our\nresults in form of graphs show quite well that for a large variety of initial\nconditions both configurations are stable and stay in this exchange orbits.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 14 Aug 2017 16:51:26 GMT"}],"update_date":"2017-08-15"}
